segments.text: Try it again.
So you were ready to go back to graduate school?
Is that?
After two years, in the meantime, I'd gotten married.
And that was part of my help in getting through my master's.
I had no financial assistance.
I'm a master's, but I thought the best thing to do was to do it as quickly as possible full time, then get back on the job.
And we married in 1950, and this was the following year in 51.
We applied, or I would look very carefully at the University of Missouri.
There were only two or three universities in the country that were offering an extension education program.
Missouri was one of the first ones, and Michigan was, Michigan State was one of the others.
And I guess I was leaning toward Missouri, but in the meantime, my job, my wife got a firm teaching job offer in East Lansing, Michigan, or close to East Lansing, Michigan.
And so we took off for Michigan and did a master's there and finished in nine months.
Came back to Matagorda County as county agent in June of that year.
Describe the duties of Matagorda County agent.
Well, let me back up and tell you one little anecdote about being in Michigan.
I got very close to the people up there.
In fact, my offices were right across the hall from their field supervisor staff.
And of course, I got to know the professor, Dr. John Stone, who later was director of extension in South Dakota.
And they

from very early started talking about my staying in Michigan and working with them and I had no I was on leave from Texas A&M University but leave without pay and I had felt an obligation of coming back but I guess since they didn't offer me any financial assistance that I might have considered an offer but the anecdote was that one one of the supervisors called me in one day and
I guess they weren't right sure they wanted a Texan just yet.
Maybe they could try me out on an interim basis.
But they had one of their larger counties up in the Thumb area, Genesee County, as I recall, up in the Thumb area of Michigan, had an agent that was going to do two years of international assignment.
And they would employ me as an acting agent until he got back.
And by then, they'd have a look at me, and I could have a look at them.
I was, you know, I didn't reject because I didn't have a firm thing in Texas.
The only thing they said, you know, we'll do the best we can when you come back.
We don't know when the vacancies will be there because I was not on leave from a position.
I was on leave from the organization.
Anyway, this supervisor very solemnly asked me if I drank on the job.
No, not if I drank on the job.
He asked me if I drank.
And I thought, boy, this is a very dangerous question.
And I thought a little bit, and I said, no.
Well, I have taken a drink now and then, but never, ever, ever on the job.
And I don't think we could use you.
And I said, why?
And he said, well, there's a lot of German farmers up there, and when they have extension meetings, they serve beer in the middle of the day.
If you don't partake, you're not going to feed it.
So not thinking was a disadvantage.
But I was very cautious in my answer.
Never, ever on the job.
I said, well, I probably can't use you.
But anyway, we did have a farm offer to go to Matagorda County of Bay City.
We grabbed it and went on down there.
Matagorda County was, of course, right next to Wharton County.
The agriculture was primarily rice, beef cattle, and cotton, some grain sorghum.
It was a wonderful county to work in.
It had one major county seat town.
A lot of times, if county agents have a problem like we did in Wharton, you have two smaller towns like Wharton, the county seat, which is smaller than El Campo.
And they're always at each other's throats.
do one thing in one part, and you'd have to do the same thing in the other, and so forth.
In Matagorda, of course, they had palaces, but palaces was much smaller.
And it was a wonderful experience.
They had one of the best churches there.
A fellow named Donald was minister in the Presbyterian church there.
And we participated very actively in the church there.
And we had a very modest, but good life down there.
People treated us very well.
Now that was how far from where you'd grown up?
Well, it was on the coast, Matagorda.
No, and you grew up?
I grew up in Bexar County, close to San Antonio.
Oh, yeah, so, and the... As I said, I didn't know anything about rice when I came into that area.
And the population make up, there were a good many Germans down there?
No, down in Matagorda County, there were a lot of Czech people.
A few Czech people, a few Germans, but more Czech.
In fact, the western part of the county was heavily Czech.
And it was also the headquarters of Shanghai Pierce, if you remember.
He was a legend in that county.
In the family, there was a big pro football player named Heffelfinger.
You ever heard of him?
Pudge Heffelfinger.
He was from that area.
I think he even had a little monument back there.
But it was a nice place.
Did anybody give you any advice when you first started out?
Did anybody kind of pull you aside and try to tell you what to do or not to do?
Well, you got a lot of that.

from whom older agents okay experienced agents and others that were you know interested and you're getting off to a good start but i guess one of the first things they hammered into me i guess as a new county extension agent you feel that you have to know the answer to everything and i said you know learn very early that if you don't know say you don't know but you'll get the answer which we always could you know because we had specialists backing us up and often you can just pick up the telephone and
get the information they needed, but it's hard for a young person right out of college to say, I don't know.
What kind of staffing did you have?
Well, we had in that county four agents.
I had two agricultural agents, I had an assistant agent, and they had two women in home economics, an agent and an assistant agent, and they also had two black staff members.
But they were, at that time, housed separately from where we were housed.
But we worked together pretty closely.
And as you started off, what did you see as your primary responsibilities?
Well, I tended to see my role as more of helping the smaller farmers, because the rice farmers generally at that time were a very
Very well off group.
Those were in the 50s, and there was a good world market for rice, and they were big operators.
I mean, they farm like 800,000 acres and run cattle with it, and many of them had oil wells with it.
And they didn't really need a lot of help.
We served the rice industry very well by having once or twice a year what we called a rice day.
get all the specialists from Beaumont and Texas A&M and had marketing discussed and all of that.
And 90% of the rice farmers would attend, and that's about the main service.
Occasionally you've got some calls for that, but most of the small farmers in the county were cotton farmers and some grain sorghum.
And I spent an awful lot of time with them, organizing them, working with them.
A lot of it had to do with insect control in cotton.
Those were the days when the miracle chemicals were coming out of World War II and DDT and all of those things which are now discredited were very much in vogue.
I guess I saw myself on the forefront of what happened in terms of the use of pesticides.
The marketers of agricultural chemical companies were really marketing a lot of stuff very aggressively.
And with a lot of farmers, it really was effective at first because the insects weren't resistant and all of that.
And a lot of farmers thinking was that if a little bit is good, it would be a whole lot better.
And it wasn't that expensive in those days.
So they overused it a lot.
And we really got into some problems that were early recognizable.
There's no, as I've often stated when I was down there, there's no plant more attractive to insects than cotton.
There are at least 22 to 25 identifiable insects that thrive in cotton.
The boll weevil and the boll worm are the two main ones.
But we began to recognize early that we're getting some problems in terms of control.
In fact, at that time, Texas A&M was advocating what they called a preventive program.
You did early season spraying with
with not even looking.
You just did it because then you'd get the plant off to a good start and so forth, but then you should stop and only treat later if needed.
But what happened in the program was that as they were using these powerful hydrocarbon chemicals, when they'd fight the boll weevil, say in the month of June, they'd kill out everything.
I mean, it was sterile.
I mean, there were no beneficial insects.
The boll worm, which is the same thing that gets into your

fear of corn that you tip in, it's the same creature, they are very susceptible to lacewing flies and to ladybugs and all of that, because the female lays their eggs singly on top of them, and 99% get eaten.
And you'll have some, but if you spray or dust, and in those days they used airplanes a lot too, you just kill out everything, and when these bull worms come in,
And usually they came from the corn crop because it matured at that time.
There was nothing there.
And just overnight, you could just be devastated.
So we recognized early on that beneficial insects played a big role in this.
And we just called attention to that type of thing.
And it's about then that the entomologists began to identify that that was indeed a problem.
But I spent a lot of time trying to educate farmers on how

identify their problems and as I often said I guess I talked more people out of using chemicals than using them because they always were ready to go you know they wanted to save their crop and one of the with the problem with the Gulf Coast was in in the summertime you almost have a shower every day you put out the chemicals get a little right rain and all wash off and then you were unprotected again you probably killed some good insects in the meantime so you were really vulnerable and so
we began to learn that it was better in many, many cases not to use the pesticides.
Probably the companies didn't like that.
But I felt a very strong role to work with the smaller farmers.
There were a lot of good family farms.
We had 4-H programs that involved the children, which the assistant agent mostly worked with.
It was a very satisfying experience.
Was there any kind of advisor group?
Yeah, we had a program building committee where we had to
leaders from every community come together a couple of times a year and try to identify what they considered were the main problems of the county.
And this would not just relate to agriculture, but even community problems.
We helped organize communities.
Reagan Brown in those days had a program of community organizations.
And we'd encourage communities to organize.
And they had monthly programs on various subjects.
And it was a good contact, good meeting place.
you know, a very satisfying operation.
I guess I was there about three and a half years, and when I was invited to come to Texas A&M to an administrative position after that, I guess the, I almost changed my mind about coming.
There was a very, very

limited income farmer who was really struggling he had a large family i think he had eight or nine kids he was on a farmer's home administration loan he had very difficult times making and i guess i worked a little harder with him than i would have otherwise because he was struggling so hard to make it but totally a type of person who could not express his feelings whatsoever but the day that my decision had been announced to leave he came into my office with tears in his eyes he said
And I said, I almost backed out.
But anyway, I stayed there, as I said, about three and a half years, and then came up here in 1955, I guess.
Down there, were there many minority farmers, black or Hispanic?
Yes, there were, but we had a black staff.
They worked separately, but we worked together.
We had programs, joint programs.
What about Hispanic?
Not too many at that time.
There were some, but they were mostly in terms of migratory
people coming through, and now it's quite changed.
There are many more Hispanics there, I've noticed, than there were at that time, but there were very few Hispanics that were farm operators at that time.
But there were quite a few blacks who were farm operators, particularly in the eastern side of the county.
Were there many sharecroppers, rent farmers?
There were a lot of rent farmers, yeah, not sharecroppers.
Most of the, most people, there were a lot of rent people that
for the sake of someone who might not know the terminology of farming, explain the difference between sharecropping and rent farming.
Well, sharecropping, you actually give, physically give a share of the crop to the, to the landowner.
In renting, you either, you pay a certain percentage, at least call it thirds and fourths, things like that, and it's not actual commodity, it's the value.
You produce ten bales of cotton, you're farming on
fourth seed, you know, a fourth of that in cash, and you settled at the end of the year.
Which was better?
Renting, yeah.

Sharecropping, I mean, it was, well, another difference in sharecropping was the landowner furnished everything, and in renting, you furnished everything, and the landowner only furnished the land, but still got a certain percentage of the crop in terms of monetary
Was everybody then using mechanical equipment?
Oh yeah.
No mules or horses?
Maybe a few small, very small farmers, but tractors were essentially universally used, and as I said, in the rice industry they were extremely mechanized.
They had these huge humongous tractors then, and they did as many as three or four different operations with airplanes.
They seeded by airplane, they put fertilizers out by airplane, they put out
insecticides, herbicides, desiccants, I mean, except for plowing and combining the crop, most everything was done by airplanes.
And you reported, in terms of the administrative organizational chart, you reported to whom?
Well, there was an intermediate organization in the Extension Service called a district, made up of usually about 20 counties, and there was a
supervisor for agriculture and a supervisor for home economics, and one that I reported to was located in Richmond.
They had an office there.
My supervisor was a fellow named Silver Whitsitt who had been earlier a county agent in a neighboring county where I grew up and had been one of my role models.
I always tracked my career, and he was the one that offered me the first job when I got through with my master's.
How did you know
What were the measures of a successful county agent?
How did you know you were doing well?
Well, I guess in those days it was, I was one who always sought feedback.
How am I doing, you know, that type of thing.
And Mr. Whissett was a laid-back type of person.
He said, if you don't see me much, you're doing okay.
He said, I have to spend my time with the problem ones.
That was about the valuation feedback I got.
Am I correct, there were no quantitative measurements that the crops increased or decreased?
Oh, you made reports.
You had to make, it wasn't required by Washington.

You have to have a report, and you must, you know, you were, but it was very difficult to do because the crops are dependent on weather and everything else, but it was mostly based, what evaluations were done was a,
of organizations you had, the people you got involved, and people who attended your meetings.
In fact, every meeting you had, you reported how many people were there.
I got very good at estimating crowds.
I could look at a large crowd and say there were 632 there.
How many, can you give examples of any problems you encountered in that three years?
Well, it's a very interesting
assignment because you have to deal with all kinds of problems.

And I was, I remember when I was early in the county, I had one of the very top leaders in the county, you know, one of the movers and shakers in the counties that you had to make sure that you didn't cross, came into my office only about two or three weeks after I was on the job, and really gave me a dressing down.
I mean, from up down to the other end.
I mean, he took it on himself to evaluate.
And the problem was, he couldn't find me in the telephone book.
Can you guess why?
Because the book hadn't been printed?
He was looking in the apps.
Oh, oh, oh.
He was very apologetic.
The idea of a county agent not having a phone.
And they would call you at five o'clock in the morning.
They were up and working.
They figured the whole world was up.
And you might have come in at midnight from a night meeting, because we had a lot of night meetings.
That's the only time farmers could come in.
But it was a job that

know generally took 78 hours a week yeah just describe a typical week well it's hard that's i think one of the things that made the work interesting there were no two days alike i mean you uh you responded to requests uh we tried to i mean you did individual work but obviously when you have several thousand farmers in the county you can't visit everyone personally and we kept trying to use group methods you know if we

if we did some insect work we'd ask the farmer to invite his neighbors in and you know we'd discuss problems and we'd have demonstrations on some places where we'd invite other farmers in we'd have meetings throughout you know throughout the county at nights and weekends and all of that we used the radio we had a weekly news column every which way to get the information out to as many people as possible and you know try to get the information you know try to be proactive try to get you know if it's spring you anticipated certain problems and

And with a small county, you know, you have easy access to the radio, the newspaper, and all of that, because they're looking to fill public service time and have a weekly column in the paper, that type of thing.
And how many hours were you in the office?

Well, it got to, you know, people also complained if they could, if you weren't in the office, they'd say, well, that's all he does, he sits in his office, and there were agents that had that reputation, and others were never in the office.
So I got to the habit of just setting a day that I would be in the office.
I always was in the office, say, on Monday.
Then I also set up because Palacios was so far away, and they always felt alienated.
I worked a half a day there on Wednesdays.
And I was a member of Rotary, and I made it nice that the Rotary Club met on Wednesdays there.
And they helped me find a little place, and people wanted to catch me then in the county.
It was part of the city hall.
They'd take calls and requests when I'd come there.
There were people that wanted to talk to me and so forth and, you know, kept publications there and so forth.
But the whole effort was trying to, you know, get out information that was useful and helpful to farmers.

And I think in those days, Extension made a big impact because the farmers were kept, you know, up to date on what varieties to plant, what, you know, how to deal with insect problems and all of this.
Did you have to cope with any natural disasters?
No hurricanes, no floods?
Well, not there.
Luckily, when I was there, there were no major hurricanes, but when I went to work in Wharton as assistant

I reported the Monday after one of the worst hurricanes I ever had, and I remember going to the Danabank community, which was a Danish community on the line between Matagorda and Wharton County, that cotton bales, as you know, they weigh 500 pounds, they floated away from the cotton gin, and they were out in the fields, and they must have had 20 inches of rain after the storm came in, and
You know, if you've ever smelled a pig pen, the whole country smelled that way because it had been underwater so long and everything rotted.
It was a disaster.
And we had to do a lot of work with trying to get, helping people get back on their feet and all of that.
But that was the only major disaster I experienced.
I had one other interesting experience.
One of the rice cattle farmers there

very active in our program, one of the leaders, and they operated cattle on the coastal marsh areas, and they would, in the wintertime, they put the cattle out on the barrier islands and peninsulas, on the salt grass areas, because there was a lot of forage there, and that's the only time a year to do it, because otherwise the mosquitoes were so bad, it was impossible to keep
So they had, this particular operation had the entire southern part of Matagorda Peninsula.
And they kept their cattle out there in the winter, and then you had this huge roundup.
And he was always after me to join them in their roundups.
And I said, I can't justify doing this.
I have plenty of taste.
But he just insisted that I do it.
And it was a good experience, because it was really a throwback to the 1880s in Texas, because
They started out at the mouth of the Colorado with their chuck wagon, with a black cook.
They had about 20 or 30 horses with a lot of cowboys.
They swam all of this across the mouth of the river.
That's the only way you could access it.
And the idea was they'd go about 20 or 30 miles down to the end of the peninsula, and then round up the cattle and come back and swim them back across the river.
Because when the spring came, they had to get them into interior lands.

I hadn't ridden a horse in a long time, and he and I rode down there, and I suspect we must have ridden 150 miles that day, because not only, the truck wagon was right on the beach where the surf had made a hard surface, but he kept crisscrossing, checking windmills, checking salt blocks, and all of this, and I would have died if I had stayed there another day.
It was wonderful eating there under the stars and everything, but
He had arranged for a plane to pick me up the next morning, and I was so sore I could barely walk for a week.
And if I had, as I said, if I had a way to ride another day, I'm sure I would have been absolutely incapacitated.
Right.
That was almost a half century ago.
How has the farm economy, the agriculture economy of that county changed in these 50 years?
Well, I'm not, I haven't been back there very often, but I can observe because a lot of times we, uh,
host international visitors there and visit counties and so forth.
The reality of farming nowadays is that there are very few bona fide farmers left as such.

I remember we had a Chinese delegation here a few years ago, about 15 people, and we took them to a neighboring county, and they were very much interested in this particular question, and even though this was considered a top agricultural county, one of them asked them the question of how many

farmers do you really have that depend you know basically on on farming for their life and he was kind of pressed against the wall and he said he'd have a hard time naming a dozen that would fit that category you know full-time farming farm nearly everyone nowadays it has off the farm employment or their wife works off the farm they've got to have some way of having a regular income because you have
all kinds of monthly things to take care of.
And many farmers do work off the farm now.
And of course, there are many.
And there's the other kind of people who have the attachment to the land who, once they get some resources, will buy a little place.
So they cause a lot of activity for the agents because many of them are unknowledgeable about agriculture when they buy a place and they want to raise a few cattle and horses and things like that.
Have the crops changed down there?
Not too much.
There's been a great big increase in Texas of corn production.
I can remember growing up, when we used to grow corn, we'd make 15, 20 bushels.
We thought we made a reasonable crop.

They regularly produce in Texas the same kind of yields now they do in the corn belt, like 100 bushels, over 100 bushels an acre, with modern varieties, fertilizers, this type of thing, early maturing varieties.
So there's lots of corn grown in Texas, a lot of grain sorghum.
Rice continues.
They've had their difficulties.
Cotton has gone out in many areas, particularly in the eastern part of the states, only in the bottom lands, like here in Brazos County.
drive over to Austin, there are a few little spots of cotton left that
I know like in the community I grew up in, we had three cotton gins when I was growing up, working 24 hours a day from August through December.
All gone.
People that try to grow cotton have to go miles and miles to get their cotton gins.
Right.
That's, in my case, in Garland, Dallas suburb.
Exactly the same.
There were three gins.
My grandparents thought that the co-op gin was communistic.
And they, there were two private owned and then one co-op.
And I don't know where the nearest gin is now.
Well, that's what, there was a little revival of interest in some of those areas recently, but I heard some farmers had to go like over a hundred miles to, over a hundred miles to get a gin.
So you, how did you get the, how did the contact come about coming back, back here to come back to the campus?
I always had,
I guess it was related to my thesis work that I did for my master's.
I had to write a thesis in Michigan.
And they wanted somebody to give some in-depth study to the problem of staffing counties.
How many counties do you need in this county, and so forth.
And I developed a procedure working up there of how to, what we called, measure the extension workload of trying to justify whether it was
six-agent county or whatever it was.
I did that.
In fact, it got known, and I've heard run into Michigan staffers many years later that still referred to the Foxfield formula.
Anyway, that came to the attention of the administrators here, and they were concerned with the same problem, but they were also concerned with another problem of financing.
Everything up to then, the legislation authorizing extension work in Texas counties was permissive.
They just said the extension service could enter into agreements with the local county commissioners' court as to staffing and payment and so forth.
And everything was pretty informal and not structured in any which way.
I mean, if a county was willing to pay for extra agents, they wanted four.
Whether or not you could justify it or not, they'd get four.
If they wanted six, they'd get six, that type of thing.
And about that time,

I don't know if you remember, there was a lot of restructuring of the school's financing system in Texas, the Gilmer-Akin bill, where the concept was developed that the poor, so-called poor counties, that means according to tax base, would get more state support than richer counties.
I mean, it was trying to equalize the big oil counties and so forth.
And this was of interest to the administration here that they felt they had to have
a more rational way of measuring workload, too, but tying this also to how much a county should be expected to contribute.
It varied all the way from 20% to 80%.
I mean, in, say, a so-called rich county, a county that had a high tax base, if they insisted on extra agents, and the extension service felt stretching it a little,
they might only participate a little bit, but the county would pay everything, or that part of that.

But you got, started getting, the county judges started comparing things, you know, I've got as much as you've got, how come you've got this, and so they wanted some kind of a formalized structure, and I was brought in as an
